500|$|On 14 August 1880, a [...] "fanciful and {{sometimes}} wildly inaccurate fictionalising" [...] {{of the events}} of the late 1840s on the Eyre Peninsula, written by Henry John Congreve, was published in the Adelaide Observer, an Adelaide weekly newspaper, as [...] "A Reminiscence of Port Lincoln". It ascribed four murders to one Aboriginal male, stated that Easton's infant had also been murdered, said that many Aboriginal people were shot and survivors driven over a cliff, and mixed up several of the recorded details. In a letter to the editor, a correspondent noted several errors in the account, and Congreve was <b>asked</b> <b>to</b> <b>respond.</b> He stated that he never intended the story to have the [...] "weight of a historical document", and that it was written merely as [...] "illustrative of the trials and dangers of the early settlers". According to authors Robert Foster, Rick Hosking and Amanda Nettelbeck, Congreve's account was [...] "not history, but fiction designed to illustrate", which had [...] "exaggerated and distorted what had (probably) happened".|$|E
